WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6 minutes English.

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com.

3
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello, this is 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.000
And I'm Georgie. Animal testing is when living animals are used in scientific research

5
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
to find out how effective a new medicine is or how safe a product is for humans.

6
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Scientists in favour of it argue that animal testing shows whether medicines are safe or dangerous

7
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
for humans and has saved many lives. But animal rights can pain us say it's cruel and also ineffective

8
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
because animals and humans are so different.

9
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Under British law, medicines must be tested on two different types of animals.

10
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Usually starting with rats, mice or guinea pigs.

11
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:58.000
And in every day English, the term human guinea pig can be used to mean the first people to have something

12
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
tested on them. But now groups both for and against animal testing are thinking again.

13
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Extra recent development in the debate. AI.

14
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:14.000
In this program, we'll be hearing how artificial intelligence could help reduce the need for scientific

15
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.000
testing on animals.

16
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
But first, I have a question for you Georgie.

17
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:26.000
There's one commonly used medicine in particular, which is harmful for animals but safe for humans.

18
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:36.000
But what is it? A antibiotics? B. aspirin or C. Parasitamol.

19
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
I guess it's aspirin.

20
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Okay, Georgie. I'll reveal the answer at the end of the program.

21
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Christine Row is a science journalist who's interested in the animal testing debate.

22
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Here, she explains to BBC World Service program, Take Life,

23
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Some of the limitations of testing medicines on animals.

24
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Of course, you can't necessarily predict from a mouse or dog what's going to happen in a human.

25
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And there have been a number of cases where substances that are proven to be toxic in animals have been proven to be safe in humans and vice versa.

26
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
There are also, of course, animal welfare, limitations to animal testing.

27
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Most people, I think, if they had the choice would want their substances to be used on as few animals or no animals as possible.

28
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Whilst they're ensuring safety.

29
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Now, that's been a really difficult needle to thread, but AI might help to make that more possible.

30
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Christine says that medicines which are safer animals might not be safe for humans,

31
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:42.000
but the opposite is also true. What's safer humans might not be safe for animals.

32
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Christine uses the phrase vice versa to show that the opposite of what she says is also true.

33
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Christine also uses the idiom to thread the needle to describe a task which requires a lot of skill and precision,

34
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
especially one involving a conflict.

35
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Yes, medical animal testing may save human lives, but many people see it as cruel and distressing for the animal.

36
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
It's a difficult needle to thread.

37
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:18.000
But now the challenge of threading that needle has got a little easier because of artificial intelligence,

38
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
predicting how likely a new medicine is to harm humans,

39
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
involves analyzing the results of thousands of experiments,

40
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
and one thing AI is really good at is analyzing mountains and mountains of data.

41
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Here's Christine Row again, speaking with BBC World Services tech life.

42
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So AI isn't the whole picture, of course, but it's an increasingly important part of the picture.

43
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And one reason for that is that there is a huge amount of toxicology data to raid through when it comes to determining and chemical safety.

44
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.000
And on top of that, there's the staggering number of chemicals being invented all of the time.

45
00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
AI helps scientists wade through huge amounts of data.

46
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
If you wade through something, you spend a lot of time and effort doing something boring or difficult.

47
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Especially reading a lot of information.

48
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.000
AI can process huge amounts of data, and what's more,

49
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
that amount keeps growing as new chemicals are invented.

50
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Christine uses the phrase on top of that, meaning in addition to something.

51
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Often this extra thing is negative.

52
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.000
She means there's already so much data to understand,

53
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
and additionally there's even more to be understood about these new chemicals.

54
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Of course, the good news is that with AI, testing on animals could one day stop.

55
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Although Christine warns that AI is not the whole picture,

56
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:50.000
it's not a complete description of something which includes all the relevant information.

57
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Nevertheless, the news is a step forward for both animal welfare and for modern medicine.

58
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Speaking of which, what was the answer to your question Phil?

59
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
What is a commonly used medicine which is safe for humans but harmful to animals?

60
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
I guess it was aspirin.

61
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Which was the correct answer.

62
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Right. Let's recap the vocabulary we've discussed, starting with human guinea pigs,

63
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:22.000
meaning the first people to have something new tested on them.

64
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:29.000
The phrase vice versa is used to indicate that the opposite of what you have just said is also true.

65
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:37.000
To thread the needle describes a task which requires extreme skill and precision to do successfully.

66
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:45.000
The whole picture means a complete description of something which includes all the relevant information and opinions about it.

67
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.000
If you wade through something, you spend a lot of time and effort doing something boring or difficult,

68
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
especially reading a lot of information.

69
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And finally, the phrase on top of something means in addition to something,

70
00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
and that extra thing is often negative.

71
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
That's all for this week. Goodbye for now.

72
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Bye!
